'Phe benefit of the lex Cornelia is available for all sureties, forbidding the same person to be surety for the same debtor to the same creditor in the same year for more than twenty thousand sester- ces of ascertained debt; and if a ἰΡοιὲἶὲἱ zzssdssfflffifffissff dred thousand sesterces, he ean only be condemned in twenty thousand sesterces. Ascertained debt includes, besides a present loan, all money which at the time of suretyship is certain to be due, that is, which de- pends on no contingency. Accord- ingly, it includes money stipulated to be paid on a future day; for here the creditor has a vested right to a future payment.
